Data is clean as this data set was created by manually copying the data from Google which shows all Manchester Uniteds Previous results.

No data was missing as the source is credible with video proof of the football games on YouTube. - https://www.google.com/search?q=manchester+United+fixtures&rlz=1C1CHBF_enIE1027IE1037&oq=manchester+United+fixtures&gs_lcrp=EgZjaHJvbWUyBggAEEUYOdIBCDQ2MTVqMGo3qAIIsAIB&sourceid=chrome&ie=UTF-8#sie=t;/m/050fh;2;/m/02_tc;bs;hd;;;;2024-11-24T16:30:00Z

United vs City all competitions win percentage¶

Note: ETH is an abbreivation for their former Manager Eric Ten Hag Note: The comparision between ETH and Manchester City Manager Pep Guardiola is not even because ETH was sacked by Manchester United early this season.

The timeframe of comparing ETH versus Guardiola is 2.25 seasons for ETH, 3 full seasosn for Guardiola. Guardiola has the upperhand statistically as Manchester City have played more games than ETH with Manchester United which will have an influence on factors that will be analysed later in the file such as goals scored against opponents, this will likely be a lot higher for Manchester City than Manchester United.

In [4]:
# Filter the data for Manchester United and Manchester City
teams = dfUtd[(dfUtd['Home Team'].str.contains('Man United')) | (dfUtd['Home Team'].str.contains('Man City'))]

# Extract the team names and win percentages
team_names = ['Manchester United', 'Manchester City']
win_percentages = [
    teams[teams['Home Team'] == 'Man United']['Win Percentage'].mean(),  # Average win percentage for Man United
    teams[teams['Home Team'] == 'Man City']['Win Percentage'].mean()  # Average win percentage for Man City
]

# Create the bar chart
bars = plt.bar(team_names, win_percentages, color=['red', 'lightblue'], label=['Manchester United', 'Manchester City'])

# Adding labels and title
plt.xlabel('Teams')
plt.ylabel('Win Percentage')
plt.title('Win Percentage Man United vs Man City, ETH first 3 seasons Versus Guardiola')

# Display the precise win percentage above the bars
for bar in bars:
    yval = bar.get_height()
    plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2, yval, f'{yval:.2f}%', ha='center', va='bottom')

# Display the bar chart
plt.show()

# Filter Premier League games for Manchester United from dfUtd
dfUnited = dfUtd[(dfUtd['Competition'] == 'Premier League') &
                 ((dfUtd['Home Team'] == 'Man United') | (dfUtd['Away Team'] == 'Man United'))]

# Filter Premier League games for Manchester City from dfUtd
dfCity = dfUtd[(dfUtd['Competition'] == 'Premier League') &
               ((dfUtd['Home Team'] == 'Man City') | (dfUtd['Away Team'] == 'Man City'))]

# Count Wins for Manchester United and Manchester City
united_wins = len(dfUnited[dfUnited['Result'] == 'W'])
city_wins = len(dfCity[dfCity['Result'] == 'W'])

# Count total games played by Manchester United and Manchester City in the Premier League
united_games_played = len(dfUnited)
city_games_played = len(dfCity)

# Calculate win percentages
united_win_percentage = (united_wins / united_games_played) * 100 if united_games_played > 0 else 0
city_win_percentage = (city_wins / city_games_played) * 100 if city_games_played > 0 else 0

# Print win percentages
print(f"Manchester United Win Percentage in Premier League: {united_win_percentage:.2f}%")
print(f"Manchester City Win Percentage in Premier League: {city_win_percentage:.2f}%")

# Calculate total count of goals and average goals per game for Manchester United
total_goals = 0

def calculate_goals(row):
    try:
        if row['Home Team'] == 'Man United':
            return int(row['Home Score'].split()[0])
        elif row['Away Team'] == 'Man United':
            return int(row['Away Score'].split()[0])
    except ValueError:
        return 0
    return 0

# Apply function to calculate goals scored by Manchester United
dfUtd['United Goals'] = dfUtd.apply(calculate_goals, axis=1)

total_goals = dfUtd['United Goals'].sum()
number_of_games = len(dfUtd[(dfUtd['Home Team'] == 'Man United') | (dfUtd['Away Team'] == 'Man United')])
average_goals_per_game = total_goals / number_of_games if number_of_games > 0 else 0

# Print total count of goals and average goals per game
print(f"Total goals scored by Manchester United: {total_goals}")
print(f"Average goals per game scored by Manchester United: {average_goals_per_game:.2f}")

Total goals scored by Manchester United: 229
Average goals per game scored by Manchester United: 1.57

# Calculate total goals conceded for Manchester United and Manchester City
def calculate_goals_conceded_united(row):
    try:
        if row['Home Team'] == 'Man United':
            return int(row['Away Score'].split()[0])
        elif row['Away Team'] == 'Man United':
            return int(row['Home Score'].split()[0])
    except ValueError:
        return 0
    return 0

def calculate_goals_conceded_city(row):
    try:
        if row['Home Team'] == 'Man City':
            return int(row['Away Score'].split()[0])
        elif row['Away Team'] == 'Man City':
            return int(row['Home Score'].split()[0])
    except ValueError:
        return 0
    return 0

dfUtd['United Goals Conceded'] = dfUtd.apply(calculate_goals_conceded_united, axis=1)
dfUtd['City Goals Conceded'] = dfUtd.apply(calculate_goals_conceded_city, axis=1)

total_goals_conceded_united = dfUtd['United Goals Conceded'].sum()
total_goals_conceded_city = dfUtd['City Goals Conceded'].sum()

def parse_score(score):
    try:
        return int(score.split()[0])
    except ValueError:
        return 0

Linear Regression¶

Prediction for Manchester United, How many games will they win lose draw in the Premier league this season.

As football has a lot of moving components and factors, also ETH has left Manchester United as a result due to poor performances (during the process of this case study). It would be a complex method to attempt to make an accurate prediction based on playing styles of the new Manager Ruben Amorim.

It was decided to use Linear regression which predicts future results based on historical results. This will predict the number of wins losses and draws in the premier league which will be indicative of where Manchester United will finish with in the Premier league for the 2024/25 Season based on all their previous Premier League results under ETH.

A new dataset called "Man_UnitedWinsRegression.csv" containing only Manchester United Results under ETH has been used for linear regression the target variable will be wins in the premier league. 3 points for a win will determine how many points Manchester United will get judging by their previous Premier League this and the previous two seasons.

In [32]:
# Load the dataset
df = pd.read_csv("Man_UnitedWinsRegression.csv")

# Filter for Premier League matches only
df_premier_league = df[df['Competition'] == 'Premier League']

# Checking if there are rows after filtering
print(f"Number of rows after filtering for Premier League: {len(df_premier_league)}")

Number of rows after filtering for Premier League: 80

Interpretation of results¶

MSE measures the average squared difference between the predicted values and the actual values in the test set. It gives a sense of how well the model fits the data.

Interpretation: An MSE (for wins) 0.81 means that, on average, the squared difference between the predicted cumulative wins and the actual cumulative wins is 0.81. This is a relatively low MSE, indicating that the model predictions are close to the actual values, although there's still some room for error.

Context: Since cumulative wins are being predicted, the low MSE suggests that the model is accurate in predicting the seasons win total trend. Lower MSE generally implies better predictive accuracy.

The coefficient slope means - for all the games in the Premier League Manchester United have won, on average for every game left in the 2024/25 Premier league season Manchester United will win 0.53 games.

Example: If Man United have started off this season with two wins and two Draws, this mans with a Coefficient slope of 0.53 (38 Premier League Games - 4 games played = 34). 0.53 X 34 = 18.02 Wins

18.02 + 2 (2 of their games won already) = 20.02 -> 20 wins (You cannot win 20.02 games in Football)

The intercepts main functions is to try fit the regression line to fit the trend of the data. A line graph wont be used to display this as the primary focus of this case study is to attempt to predict the points total Manchester United will finish on.

# Filter for Premier League matches only
df_premier_league = df[df['Competition'] == 'Premier League'].copy()

# Encode Result column for wins and draws
df_premier_league['Win_Binary'] = df_premier_league['Result'].map({'W': 1, 'D': 0, 'L': 0})
df_premier_league['Draw_Binary'] = df_premier_league['Result'].map({'D': 1, 'W': 0, 'L': 0})

# Calculate cumulative wins and draws after each game
df_premier_league['Cumulative_Wins'] = df_premier_league['Win_Binary'].cumsum()
df_premier_league['Cumulative_Draws'] = df_premier_league['Draw_Binary'].cumsum()

# Create a game number column to use as a time-based feature
df_premier_league['Game_Number'] = np.arange(1, len(df_premier_league) + 1)

# Define feature (Game_Number) and targets (Cumulative_Wins and Cumulative_Draws)
X = df_premier_league[['Game_Number']]
y_wins = df_premier_league['Cumulative_Wins']
y_draws = df_premier_league['Cumulative_Draws']

# Split the data into training and testing sets for wins and draws
X_train, X_test, y_train_wins, y_test_wins = train_test_split(X, y_wins, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
X_train, X_test, y_train_draws, y_test_draws = train_test_split(X, y_draws, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Initialize and train the linear regression models for cumulative wins and draws
model_wins = LinearRegression()
model_draws = LinearRegression()

model_wins.fit(X_train, y_train_wins)
model_draws.fit(X_train, y_train_draws)

# Calculate metrics for the wins model
y_pred_wins = model_wins.predict(X_test)
mse_wins = mean_squared_error(y_test_wins, y_pred_wins)
slope_wins = model_wins.coef_[0]
intercept_wins = model_wins.intercept_

# Calculate metrics for the draws model
y_pred_draws = model_draws.predict(X_test)
mse_draws = mean_squared_error(y_test_draws, y_pred_draws)
slope_draws = model_draws.coef_[0]
intercept_draws = model_draws.intercept_

# Display metrics for cumulative wins
print("Cumulative Wins Model - Mean Squared Error:", mse_wins)
print("Cumulative Wins Model - Coefficient (Slope):", slope_wins)
print("Cumulative Wins Model - Intercept:", intercept_wins)

print("================================================================")
print("================================================================")

# Display metrics for cumulative draws
print("Cumulative Draws Model - Mean Squared Error:", mse_draws)
print("Cumulative Draws Model - Coefficient (Slope):", slope_draws)
print("Cumulative Draws Model - Intercept:", intercept_draws)

Conclusions and Restrictions of Manchester United Case study¶

A relatively accurate prediction has been made for Manchester United to finish on 69 points which mathematically is possible, but optimistic given they have had a change of Manager from ETH to Ruben Amorim recently. Amorim likely plays a different style of football compared to ETH meaning potentially a large learning curve for the Manchester United players to adapt to Amorim's playstyle which could negatively affect results in the short/mid term.

A limitation of this case study is: Historical data from the previous 2 seasons are used to predict how many points Manchester United will finish with in the Premier League which is not always the correct approach because in this context Manchester Uniteds performances have been inconsistent for the last 10 seasons.

This limitation occurred because:

  1. There was too few games played this season to give a points indication, independently of previous seasons, hence why the data was included.

  2. While building this case study ETH left Manchester United which slightly changed the purpose of the case study with a points prediction being the main goal of this. It was intended in the next file to dig deep into match stattics but since ETH left there is no longer a purpose in trying to analyse the game details (i.e. Posession, Shots etc..) showing some of their biggest wins/losses to get an indication of what exatly is occuring in the games and why its happening at least from a statistical perspective.

However Manchester City's performances have been very consistent since Pep Guardiola has been manager it would be a relatively safe presumption to make as Manchester City have won the League for the previous 4 consecutive seasons. 6 Leagues titles in total for Guardiola in his 8 year reign so far at Manchester City.

A good time to revisit this case study may be around this time next season where more data and results will be available to make another prediction where Man United finish in the Premier league and do it independently of other premier league seasons noting their performances from season to season can be relatively volatile.

Difference between Manchester United and Manchester City¶

As the bar charts show, the gap in performance is large from a football perspective Manchester City are arguably the best team in world football as it stands, when you look at visuals of goals scored, average goals scored per game, goals conceded Manchester City are remarkably stronger than Manchester United at least judging by the Premier League and other competitions.

Perspecitve: This case study City were analysed under playing more games where they are more likely to slighlty dip in performance yet the majoruty of the statistics are largely stronger than Manchester United.
